title: For Sale:  NEW:  Keltec OD "Green" KSG shotgun
postcontent: New in the box. $900.00 tax includedThe KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3". This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil. The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward. We can only accept cash, we no longer accept CC's.

title: For Sale:  Remington 870 Combat Shotgun
postcontent:
This is the ultimate Home Defense combat shotgun. It is built on a Remington 870.

The nation's leading defender. For a half century the Remington Model 870 has been the pump shotgun of choice for government agencies. With over 10 million produced to date, it remains the standard by which all pump actions are measured. Its dual, non-binding action bars deliver ultra-smooth, reliable cycling. The ultimate pump shotgun, the Model 870 stands the test of time, extreme conditions and duty.
•Non-binding twin action bars provide smoothest/surest pump operation
•Receiver milled from solid block of steel
•3" chamber accepts all 2 ¾" and 3" 12-gauge shells
•Steel-lined/grooved fore-end for a stronger grip
•Breech block locks into barrel extension for strength and consistent head space
•Balanced sear and inertia firing pin prevents discharge unless action is closed and trigger is pulled
•Flexitab feeding system prevents a misfeed from jamming the shotgun
•Cross-bolt safety

The Modifications to the firearm are as follows.

It has a Knoxx Specops stock on it. It is adjustable to fit any person or can accommodate body armor. This is NOT a cheap stock like an ATI. This is meant for serious duty use.

The forend is a Surefire Remington 870 Weaponlight. This light is blindingly bright and great to easily identify anything that goes bump in the night. The forend alone retails for $300 dollars and they rarely come on the used market. It has buttons for continuous light and a pressure pad for momentary light.

The Firearm is coated in Ceracote H baked on finish. It is extremely durable and abrasive and chemical resistant. To have a long gun refinished in this coating runs about $200. The process is very labor intensive but results in the most durable firearm finish available and is well worth the money.

There is a single point sling mount between the stock and receiver for carrying the firearm with a single point sling but there are also mounts included to run a 2 point sling as well.

It has a side saddle on the side of the receiver that can hold 6 shotgun shells. This allows the firearm to have 13 rounds of ammunition carried on it before adding extra with your preferred method of carrying shells.

The magazine extension allows the firearm to have 7 shots including one in the chamber to allow for the most firepower before a reload possible. It functions reliably and is very heavy duty. The magazine spring is extra power to ensure that even under the most demanding conditions, the firearm will always reliably feed a new shell.

All of the internals were upgraded to new extreme duty police parts. This includes heavier springs for the hammer, shell lifter, and tigger sear and upgraded parts that are all machined and not MIM.

The barrel is an 18 inch factory Remington barrel with a cylinder bore. That means that the barrel has the optimal spread for close quarter combat and can fire any ammunition you put in it from birdshot to buckshot and slugs. It is the shortest barrel that can be legally fitted to the firearm. It can handle both 2 3/4" and 3" ammunition and has functioned flawlessly with both.

This is the ultimate combat shotgun and it is a shotgun you can trust your life to. I would not hesitate to grab this gun if I was having a home invasion. This shotgun will more than exceed your expectations for a shotgun and is the best that money can buy. All the parts and work for this shotgun total more than $1200. I am asking $650 for this shotgun. Compare to any similar shotgun on gunbroker and you will see that this is a good deal. Email me or text 3one3five4nine9nine5one.  I am open to trades of equal value (preferably handguns or AR15).

title: For Sale/Trade:  * Price drop * 1952 Hal Hartley Custom Tiger Maple Rifle. FN Columbian 30-06 ... Piece of history!
postcontent:
Not in a big hurry to sell this, if I sell it at all. But I thought that I would post it up here and see what kind of a response that I get. This is an absolutely beautiful rifle, pictures do not do it justice.

For those of you who don't know who Hal Hartley was, do a little research. This was THE top rifle maker for years and years, during the 50's and through the 70's. His craftsmanship is not only unmistakably beautiful but is also tremendously rare and valuable. His works graced the cover of Gun Digest many times and he has been recognized in modern publication for his work with Tiger Maple, his signature design preference. Mr. Hartley's work is few and far between nowadays; It is unfortunate that time destroys so much of past beauty. Luckily, my rifle has been kept in pristine condition as the pictures will reflect.

As I have already mentioned in the title, this is a signature tiger maple stock built on a jeweled FN 1950 Columbian action chambered in 30-06. This is not a re barreled Mauser, this is an original 1950 FN 30-06. The barrel is nicely blued and all bluing is 99%. The stock features ivory inlay as well as a 4 carat tanzanite stone embedded in the grip of the rifle. The tanzanite stone by itself is very valuable; the cut is clean and the clarity is very good. The stock also features a gorgeous hand checkering job done by Mr. Hartley. The trigger is a gold plated Timney which pulls very light. This rifle will come with the original sling, scope, and scope rings. Scope is a Bushnell Command Post Chief 2. Weaver rings. 

Some of the pictures make this rifle look a little darker than it actually is. I apologize for the poor picture quality. More pictures available upon request. As far as my price, I am OBO, and willing to hear any and all offers for the rifle based on your evaluation of its value. Please be reasonable. I will accept trades. I've said it once but I will say it again, I do not have to sell this, I am not convinced that I want to. But I am willing to see all offers.

$8,750 OBO

So earlier today I was gonna meet with David Alexander to trade his glock 17 for my bushmaster c15. We met at a gas station in fife but he wanted to go some where with less people to check out the ar better without people looking. He was with a friend, a big guy with 2 gold teeth in the bottom. So I followed him close to the ports and we found a little area to park and inspect each other's weapons before going to a FFL. He showed me his g17 that was in his trunk then I brought my ar to his trunk so he can check it out. At that point a security guard came around and said we gotta leave. He had a battery charger in his trunk which he gave to me and said thanks for the jump so the guard didn't get suspicious. We started driving to another location to continue our transaction. Then he decided to drive recklessly to lose me. I followed him for a little until it got to sketchy to continue. The AR wasn't worth crashing or causing an accident over. I tried to message him but he blocked me and deleted his post. I have screen shots of some of his profile pics.
